Stage 3: Final Exploratory Analysis

Elliane Hall and Conner Harwood

Topic and Motivation

This project investigates how water use within the Utah portion of the Great Salt Lake Basin contributes to yearly variations in Great Salt Lake (GSL) water levels. Our research explores relationships between GSL levels and water use, population, and precipitation. Utilizing an OLS linear regression model, the study aims to identify specific water use types, such as agricultural and industrial, that offer the most explanation for declining lake levels.

Utah has been the fastest growing state since 2010, and much of this growth comes in counties closely connected to the Great Salt Lake. The GSL has been facing dangerously low and decreasing water levels over the past several decades. If this trend continues, the economic, environmental, and ecological consequences to the region would be drastic. Declining lake levels expose lake bed containing dangerous heavy metals, such as lead, mercury, and arsenic. As the exposed lake bed dries up, winds kick up dust storms that pose significant health risks to the surrounding communities. Lower lake levels also negatively impact the biology and wildlife that are dependent on a healthy lake. These include brine shrimp and one of the largest populations of migratory birds in North America. Economic sectors reliant on the GSL, including recreation and industry, are also negatively affected by declining levels.

While climate change is expected to play a role in the future, current GSL level declines are primarily attributed to anthropogenic activities stemming from water development (source). Understanding the impact of water use in the Great Salt Lake Basin, coupled with population pressures and a changing climate, is crucial for the lakes health and the well-being of surrounding communities.

Furthermore, agriculture is the largest water user in the state of Utah, using 68% of the states water supply, yet it only generates 0.2% of Utahs GDP (source). Examining water use trends in this sector is essential for formulating policies that mitigate its impact on the Great Salt Lake.

Data Descriptions

Water Use Obtained through the Utah Division of Water Rights here, this data includes all water rights holders in Utah dating back to 1959. Utah has surprisingly complete water use data that is publicly available. It has records on total monthly water usage in gallons for each water user, and breaks down this usage by type of use (e.g.agricultural, commercial, water supplier), as well as several other variables of interest. We are looking at data on water usage for users whose coordinates lie within the GSL Basin. The data does not indicate whether water usage records are consumptive uses, which have much larger impacts on the Great Salt Lake than non-consumptive uses, as this water is not returned to the watershed. Though this is a limitation of the data, we will still be able to gain a solid understanding of water usage impacts on the Great Salt Lake.

Great Salt Lake Elevation Levels Obtained through the USGS using the dataRetrieval package in R, weve gathered daily water level observations dating back to 1966. The two relevant gauges are the Saltair Boat Harbor gauge in the South arm of the lake and the gauge near Saline, UT in the North arm (the lake was split into two arms by a railroad causeway in the 1950s). Though the water levels of the two arms are typically very similar, weve used the average of the two gauge values for our observations. The gauges measure surface level elevation above sea level in feet.

Great Salt Lake Volume Obtained through HydroShare here, this data contains monthly volume of the GSL dating back to 1847. Volumes are expressed in cubic meters and were calculated by the data providers using lake levels and bathymetry data of the GSL.

County Resident Populations Obtained through Federal Reserve Economic Data (FRED) here, this data contains yearly resident population numbers in each Utah county for all years dating back to 1970.

Precipitation Obtained through NOAA here, this data contains monthly total precipitation records in each Utah county for all years dating back to 1959.

Utah Counties Shapefile Obtained through the State of Utah Open Data Catalog here, this data contains a shapefile with geographic boundaries of all Utah counties.

Great Salt Lake Basin Shapefile Obtained through HydroShare here, this data contains a shapefile with geographic boundaries of the Great Salt Lake and of the Great Salt Lake Basins 4 subbasins. A significant portion of the western half of the West Desert Subbasin is omitted from the data, which has previously been deemed not relevant for hydrology studies of the GSL.

Data Processing

Water Use The water use .csv file included two data tables containing different variables and information on entities with water user rights. One of the tables contained the monthly water usage data were interested, and the other table had county information which we merged with the first table after cleaning them both. This data required significant cleaning. After standard cleaning steps like selecting and renaming relevant variables and dropping duplicates, we dedicated a lot of time to addressing NAs, 0s, and outliers, as well as restricting the data to include the most relevant water users. We converted the dataset to long format by monthly water use after most of our cleaning as it was easier for our purposes to work with it in wide format.

Observations missing year, as well as those containing no water usage values, were removed. We also removed observations with missing or invalid latitude and longitude values since we used the Great Salt Lake Basin shapefile to filter out observations that did not overlap with its geometry. After filtering out these observations, the unique counties were extracted to determine the 12 counties to download population and precipitation data for.

Some observations had a non-zero value for total usage in a year, but their monthly usage values were all 0. Looking at the original database on the Utah Division of Water Rights website, the total usage numbers seemed to be correct, and the 0s for the monthly data was simply a lack of records. This occurred mostly in earlier years. Since for some of our analysis we look at yearly aggregate data rather than monthly, we kept these observations in the dataset.

We restricted our dataset to 1996 and on since that is when reporting seems to be (mostly) fully complete for most use types. Sewage Treatment and Mining use types did not have as many complete years, so we filtered them out to ensure that we had an appropriately long time period to work with.

Some observations were removed that had water usage values magnitudes higher than the rest of the data set. Since the original database did not show values this high, we felt it safe to remove them entirely as they likely were not created during the data generating process. There are also several observations with negative monthly values, but the yearly values are positive for these observations. This aligns with the original data and indicates a return of water back to the basin. Weve chosen to keep these observations.

Great Salt Lake Elevation Levels For the GSL levels data, we first cleaned the North Arm and South Arm data sets separately. Not much cleaning was necessary; we primarily selected and renamed relevant variables, then collapsed the daily water level values into monthly means for each year. The North and South Arms were then merged into one data set, and the average levels between the two gauges were calculated to give us the main water level values were interested in.

Great Salt Lake Volume The GSL volume data required minimal cleaning. Relevant variables were selected and renamed, and the date column was separated into year and month. Volume was later on converted from cubic meters to gallons to have consistent units with the water use data.

County Resident Populations We downloaded this data from FRED for our specific counties of interest, and it came in an already mostly clean Excel file. All that was needed for further cleaning was reading the file into RStudio, converting to long format, extracting year from the date column, and changing some variables names. This data was then merged with the water use data by county and year. Populations were expressed in thousands of people, which we converted to actual population by multiplying by 1000.

Precipitation Data The precipitation data was downloaded separately for each county, from which we then cleaned the date values and added a county variable for each county. That data was then appended into one data set, and we did a few checks of the data before finalizing it. Overall, not much cleaning was needed here.

Utah Counties Shapefile The only cleaning needed for this data was selecting and renaming relevant variables and converting the county values to title format.

Great Salt Lake Basin Shapefile After selecting and renaming relevant variables, we filtered out the Strawberry Reservoir. This reservoir is often relevant for hydrology studies of the Great Salt Lake, but it is not a GSL subbasin and is not relevant for our purposes of studying water use. We transformed this shapefile to have the same coordinate reference system as the Utah counties shapefile. From here, we restricted the geometry so that it included only the portion of the Great Salt Lake Basin that lies within Utah. We did this using st_intersection from the sf package with the Utah counties shapefile. This was later used to restrict the water use dataset to include only water rights users located within the GSL Basin.

Master Dataset Since we very thoroughly cleaned our individual datasets, merging was straightforward. We simply did a few many-to-one merges with left_join and our master dataset was ready. During our exploratory analysis, we created yearly aggregate datasets from the master dataset. This entailed taking either the sum of all months in each year (water use) or the mean of all months in each year (population, precipitation, GSL levels and volume). We log transformed water usage variables in a few instances during exploratory analysis due to positive skewness and outliers.

Data Limitations Through our best efforts of cleaning and processing the data, we came across a number of limitations. The outliers in the water use data were concerning. Though we are confident in our decision to remove them, we cannot be certain that they are illegitimate data without speaking directly with the Utah Division of Water Rights (we attempted this numerous times but they did not respond). Given the inconsistency in when certain water use types began fully reporting their data, restricting our data to 1996 and beyond filtered out a lot of potentially useful observations. Having a longer time frame of data would give a more accurate assessment of the impacts of water use on Great Salt Lake levels. Consumptive vs.non-consumptive water use is another limitation. Our data does not specify between these two, and consumptive use is of much greater concern to declining GSL levels as this water is not returned to the watershed. Some use types, such as agricultural and power, are understood to have consumptive use. Other use types are less clear. Further research and/or data reporting on this front would be greatly beneficial. Overall, despite these limitations, we are confident that our data provides a solid understanding of the impacts of water usage on Great Salt Lake levels.

Exploratory Analysis

Great Salt Lake Levels and Agricultural Water Use

Here we plot yearly Great Salt Lake elevations measured as feet above sea level, with log yearly agricultural water usage below. These trends show a clear rise in agricultural water use along with a consistently declining Great Salt Lake. We also added a line at 4198 feet - this number represents the minimum water level needed to support a healthy ecosystem. The GSL continues to fall well below this important threshold, with agricultural water usage showing no signs of slowing down.

Water Use by Use Type

We looked at water use trends broken down by the type of water use. Most uses show a steady but small increase over time, with agricultural uses increasing at a significantly faster rate than other uses. Water suppliers, industrial, and mining water uses have remained high with little fluctuations across years. However, we find that agricultural recently overtook mining in water usage. If the upward trend continues, agriculture will become an even more significant water user in the Great Salt Lake basin.

Precipitation and Water Usage

This plot shows how water use within each use type changes as precipitation in the Great Salt Lake Basin counties increases. Most uses see either no change or a small decrease in use as precipitation increases, with agricultural uses declining more significantly. This aligns with what we would expect, as agricultural practices such as irrigation may not be as necessary with higher levels of rainfall. It also shows a problematic trend the other way; in drier years, the agricultural sector increases its water usage. This, in conjunction with the lack of precipitation, could exacerbate declining lake levels.

Per Capita Water Usage

Here we divided total yearly water usage in the GSL Basin by the total population of all the Basin counties in that year to obtain a measure for per capita water usage. The data show a positive relationship here, meaning that with an already sharply increasing population, water usage is increasing at an even faster rate.

Bigger Picture

Overall, the data show that the Great Salt Lake is showing no signs of reversing its decline, and water users in the Great Salt Lake Basin dont seem to be curbing their usage. The health, economic, environmental, and ecological impacts of a shrinking Great Salt Lake have already been felt and seen. Without significant behavioral and policy changes in this region, the GSL could reach irreversibly low water levels in the not-so-distant future. Our next step will be predicting when lake levels will reach these lows using what weve observed with water usage in the Great Salt Lake Basin, along with precipitation and population trends for a more accurate measure.
